{title: To You and Yours from Me and Mine}
{artist: George Hamilton IV}
{composer: Written by Bill Anderson}

[C]Wedding bells are ringing [G7]on two sides of [C]town tonight
One [G7]wedding is at seven one's at [C]nine[C7]
A [F]pair of old [G7]sweethearts will hold [F]their new sweethearts so [C]tight
Best of luck to you and [F]yours from me and [C]mine[C7]
To [F]you and yours may [G7]happiness flow [C]free
May [F]you find in him the [G7]faith you lost in [C]me
And although I don't love her yet [F]perhaps I will in time
Best of [G7]luck to you and yours from me and [C]mine
I'm afraid to say I [G7]do for fear I [C]really don't
[G7]Afraid my conscience might not walk the [C]line[C7]
For [F]even though I'll [G7]kiss her lips it's [F]your lips that I [C]want
That's a difference in you and [F]yours and me and [C]mine[C7]
Repeat #2